    "slug": "somali-national-election-commission-head-arrives-in-dhusamareb-voter-card-distribution-resumes-in-galkayo",
    "summary": "The chairman of Somalia’s National Independent Electoral and Boundaries Commission, Abdikarin Ahmed Hassan, arrived in Dhusamareb today to oversee election preparations. Simultaneously, the commission resumed voter card distribution in Galkayo, signaling progress toward Somalia’s one-person-one-vote elections.",
    "content": "The chairman of Somalia’s National Independent Electoral and Boundaries Commission, Abdikarin Ahmed Hassan, arrived in Dhusamareb, the capital of Galmudug state, on Sunday. His visit is aimed at overseeing preparations for the upcoming one-person-one-vote elections in the region. The commission has been intensifying its activities across various areas of Galmudug to ensure the electoral process proceeds on schedule.\n\nOn the same day, the commission reopened the distribution of voter ID cards in the Galkayo district of Galmudug. This step is critical for enabling residents to participate in the forthcoming elections. The distribution had been paused earlier, but the commission has not disclosed the reasons for the suspension or its resumption.\n\nThe chairman, Abdikarin Ahmed Hassan, is expected to hold meetings with local officials and community leaders during his stay in Dhusamareb. These consultations are part of broader efforts to address logistical and security challenges that could affect the electoral timeline. Somalia has been working toward direct universal suffrage for decades, and the current process is seen as a key milestone.\n\nFor the Somali diaspora, the successful implementation of one-person-one-vote elections represents a historic shift from the clan-based power-sharing system that has dominated Somali politics since the early 2000s. The diaspora community has long advocated for transparent and inclusive elections that give every citizen a voice. The resumption of voter card distribution in Galkayo, a city with significant clan diversity and periodic tensions, is a promising sign that electoral preparations are on track.\n\nHowever, challenges remain, including security threats from militant groups and administrative hurdles in remote areas. The commission’s proactive oversight, including the chairman’s field visit, suggests a commitment to overcoming these obstacles. The diaspora watches closely as these developments unfold, hoping for a peaceful and credible electoral process.\n\nRead the original report from Goobjoog here: https://goobjoog.com/2026/07/19/guddoomiyaha-guddiga-doorashooyinka-qaranka-oo-gaaray-dhuusamareeb-iyadoo-gaalkacyo-dib-looga-furay-bixinta-kaararka-codbixiyeyaasha/",
